, England":"Somerset, England","Monney Castle, Monney, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Nunney, Somerset, England":"Nunney, Somerset, England","Wincanton, Somerset, England":"Wincanton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Holbrook, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","of Nunney, Som., Eng.":"Nunney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hussey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a nickname for someone who habitually wore a distinctive pair of boots or gaiters, from Old French <i>hosed</i>, <i>hoset</i>, <i>housé</i>, Middle English <i>hosey</i>, <i>hus(s)y</i>,‘booted, gaitered’ (from Latin <i>hosatus</i>).","English: status name or nickname from Middle English <i>hus(e)wyf</i> ‘mistress of a family; wife of a householder’ (a compound of Old English <i>hūs</i> ‘house’ + <i>wīf</i> ‘woman’). Though originally a woman's name, it is often found as a male surname, presumably in a derogatory sense. The vocabulary word became <i>hussie</i>, with the meaning ‘disreputable woman’, in the 16th century; the surname, however, is not associated with this meaning.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’. This was the name of a bardic family associated with the Maguires of Fermanagh, also Anglicized as   Oswell   or   Oswald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hosea","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  . Similarity with the Old Testament prophet's name Hosea (see 3 below) is accidental.","English: in Scotland, where the name is more common, it is sometimes a variant of   Hosie  , itself a form of   Hussey  , or else a variant of   Hossack  .","African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania): from the Biblical personal name <i>Hosea</i>. In the Old Testament, Hosea was a prophet who married a prostitute in order to illustrate Israel's unfaithfulness to God."]},{"name":"Hosie","meanings":["Scottish (northeast Scotland): variant of Irish   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Hassey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Oswell","meanings":["English: variant of   Oswald  .","Irish (Ulster): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’ (see   Hussey  )."]},{"name":"Hosey","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":23,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Matilda Hussey was born in 1359, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Edmund Hussey, was 32 and her mother, Lady Joanna Whitton, was 29. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Sir Philip de la Mare. She died in 1396, in Somerset, England, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1359–1396":"1359–1396","1349–1411":"1349–1411","1349–1412":"1349–1412","1354–1400":"1354–1400","1347–1396":"1347–1396","1374–1413":"1374–1413","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1384–1450":"1384–1450","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1330–1411":"1330–1411","abt 1380":"umbes 1380","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1450":"1450","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1327":"1327","1349":"1349","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1413":"1413","1412":"1412","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1354":"1354","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Monney Castle, Monney, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nunney, Somerset, England":"Nunney, Somerset, England","Wincanton, Somerset, England":"Wincanton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Holbrook, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Nunney, Som., Eng.":"Nunney, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1359–1396":"1359–1396","1349–1411":"1349–1411","1349–1412":"1349–1412","1354–1400":"1354–1400","1347–1396":"1347–1396","1374–1413":"1374–1413","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1384–1450":"1384–1450","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1330–1411":"1330–1411","abt 1380":"noin 1380","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1450":"1450","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1327":"1327","1349":"1349","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1413":"1413",